You may miss this place as its a humble place located at the corner of the street! But, look for it & go for it.. you don't wana misss the amazing french "soul" food, which definitely is food for the soul! Best dish is Shrimp & Grits.. so full of flavors, it has porridge cheese with bacon & tomato sauce.. leaves you asking for more!! Crawfish Beignets, we tried just a piece & it was nice & crusty! For sure is on my top list of restaurants in SF ! Their BFC Fried chicken is great (as heard), trying it the next time I'm in the city!

I've lived in San Francisco for years, and finally got up early enough on a Sunday to beat the wait at Brenda's. I've wanted to try simply because of the 10000+ reviews of yelp and 4 star rating. We got in line at 8:30, waited about 5 minutes and were seated quickly. It's a surprisingly big space and they get people in and out fairly quick, so the line goes fast. Just don't expect to be seated quick with a large party - I think that is normal for any brunch spot. Their coffee is great, I ordered a double latte, and my husband ordered a cafe au lai. Cups are massive so it's a good portion of coffee where you'll likely never need a second cup. We ordered the beignets flight that comes with one of each (4 total) of their chocolate, plain, apple cinnamon, and crawfish beignets. I don't like crawfish so I can't leave an honest review of it, but I strongly disliked the flavor of that beignet. Their plain one was nothing to write home about, too dough-y, fairly heavy and just not amazing. Their chocolate was good with the warm chocolate filling. My favorite was the apple cinnamon. It is filled with small bits of apple coated in a honey and cinnamon mixture that adds a sweet element to the savory beignet dough. The flight is a lot of food, and I honestly took one or two bites of each and had to stop to leave room for my actual meal. As for the meal: I ordered their fried chicken Benedict with hash. The hash has great flavors and is crispy! The Benedict, however, was very disappointing. The cream biscuit was good, but really heavy. One of my poached eggs was runny, the other not so much. The sauce was really thick and sour, not a good blend of sweet and savory like it should be, and it was overpowering. The fried chicken was not seasoned well, and was honestly a little soggy, should've been crispier. I wanted to love this dish, but the flavors could've been better. I just felt like it didn't mesh well and lacked something. Service was good, and to be honest, I never put a place down for their service unless they royally screw up our orders, or if they are deliberately rude. It was very busy, we got our food quickly, and everything was correct. We were in and out fairly fast, and our server was very kind. Overall, I feel like this place has unique offerings for brunch that a lot of places in San Francisco do not offer. However, i don't feel like it lived up to the hype, and don't think I would be willing to wait an hour for it like most people do every weekend

Amazing. Must try in San Fran. Be careful on your walk there. Staff is quick, friendly, and gave great suggestions. The food was delicious and very filling.

Like many, I've always seen the line at Brenda's and could never convince myself that I had the time or interest in French Soul food. But today, I decided to go for it and I'm glad I did. Times were insane on a Sunday morning, but that's to be expected. I went in to write my name on the chalkboard and as I cluelessly tried to figure out where the chalk was, someone else wrote their name on the board (thanks, bro!) Anyway, for those that need to know, there's a few chalk pieces to the counter in a small plate to the left of the large chalkboard inside. Wait times for the weekend average 20-60 minutes and I'd say we were slightly under 60 minutes. Tables tend to turn over in cycles as food does come out fairly quickly and the wait staff are friendly and efficient. As we walked around the block, our name came up (and they passed us) but they kindly let us get seated when we came back and realized we had been passed much quicker than we thought. It's a small space with both table seating and counter seating. The menu is straight-forward with drinks, libations, and entrees. The standout items recommended to us were the beignets and the shrimp and grits. Other delicious items we saw being consumed included the fried chicken (not available a la carte until 5 pm) and the eggs benedict dishes. Our order: Creole Bloody Mary - $7. Not the strongest bloody mary I've had but tasty with cajun spices and a nice pickled okra piece. Guava Mimosa - $8. Fairly small pour for the price but refreshing. Shrimp & Grits - $15. I'm a grits newbie and didn't know what to expect. It was amazing and the melted cheese mixed with the grits is the perfect complement to the sauteed shrimp and fantastic, over-the-top spicy tomato and bacon gravy. We finished every drop. Beignets - $12. We sampled a flight and had one of every type. The famous one are the crawfish beignets and upon opening you're greeted with a molten mixture of chedder, crawfish, and scallions. The plain and chocolate are great too and we also had a Chefgiving version that featured maple, pecan and bacon. The fillings were all wonderful and if there's one minor criticism is that the beignet batter was more dense than I expected. I always envisioned more light and airy, but that could be entirely wrong and on me. Gumbo - sampled a small cup and it was piping hot and flavorful. I thought it was good, but could have used a touch more seasoning. Overall solid, but I liked the gumbo I had at the Bywater much more. Overall, despite the very long wait, I was glad to finally try Brenda's and to especially sample the great shrimp and grits. I hear they do take out and while it's not as piping hot as eating it there, maybe I'll be able to save some time. Brenda's accepts credit cards, including Amex.

Almost exactly 9 years since my last visit and what a difference. Looking back, I probably ordered the wrong things. None of what I had before was part of the house favorites. This time, I got all the right stuff: -Crawfish Beignets: If you're not into sweets, this is perfect. It's like an awesome version of a Hot Pocket. It's huge. It's full of cheese and crawfish. It comes out hot and gooey. It's dusted with a Cajun seasoning that's flavorful but not overpowering. In fact, I rubbed my beignet in all the seasoning that fell off onto my plate. -Hangtown Fry: It looks like a plain omelette when you get it but each bite of oyster makes it that much better. It's a big portion with a huge biscuit and a hefty bowl of buttery grits. -Shrimp and Grits: This is super flavorful and might induce heartburn for the weak, especially if you're having this early in the morning. At the very bottom of the large bowl are the grits. Next, you'll find a thick layer of melted cheddar. On top of that, you'll find the spicy tomato-bacon gravy. It was topped off with shrimp which was cooked tender and not over done at all. It's creamy, savory and heavy. I was only able to eat half so they packed the other half for me and it didn't look as much in the takeout container. So I think the bowl is slightly an illusion; looks bigger than it really is but the heaviness will fill you up quick. It has been quite a while but I don't remember the inside looking this hip and cool. The space has also expanded and I'm glad there was absolutely no wait at 10am on a Tuesday. I will definitely be taking any out-of-towners here in the future.

    I've lived in San Francisco for years, and finally got up early enough on a Sunday to beat the wait at Brenda's. I've wanted to try simply because of the 10000+ reviews of yelp and 4 star rating. We got in line at 8:30, waited about 5 minutes and were seated quickly. It's a surprisingly big space and they get people in and out fairly quick, so the line goes fast. Just don't expect to be seated quick with a large party - I think that is normal for any brunch spot.

    Their coffee is great, I ordered a double latte, and my husband ordered a cafe au lai. Cups are massive so it's a good portion of coffee where you'll likely never need a second cup. We ordered the beignets flight that comes with one of each (4 total) of their chocolate, plain, apple cinnamon, and crawfish beignets. I don't like crawfish so I can't leave an honest review of it, but I strongly disliked the flavor of that beignet. Their plain one was nothing to write home about, too dough-y, fairly heavy and just not amazing. Their chocolate was good with the warm chocolate filling. My favorite was the apple cinnamon. It is filled with small bits of apple coated in a honey and cinnamon mixture that adds a sweet element to the savory beignet dough. The flight is a lot of food, and I honestly took one or two bites of each and had to stop to leave room for my actual meal.

    As for the meal: I ordered their fried chicken Benedict with hash. The hash has great flavors and is crispy! The Benedict, however, was very disappointing. The cream biscuit was good, but really heavy. One of my poached eggs was runny, the other not so much. The sauce was really thick and sour, not a good blend of sweet and savory like it should be, and it was overpowering. The fried chicken was not seasoned well, and was honestly a little soggy, should've been crispier. I wanted to love this dish, but the flavors could've been better. I just felt like it didn't mesh well and lacked something.

    Service was good, and to be honest, I never put a place down for their service unless they royally screw up our orders, or if they are deliberately rude. It was very busy, we got our food quickly, and everything was correct. We were in and out fairly fast, and our server was very kind.

    Overall, I feel like this place has unique offerings for brunch that a lot of places in San Francisco do not offer. However, i don't feel like it lived up to the hype, and don't think I would be willing to wait an hour for it like most people do every weekend

    First of all, this place is interesting, trendy and fun. The location can give you pause because it's located in what can be considered a sketchy part of SF. You will be asked for change while you walk to it but overall the area is not bad.

    At first it doesn't look like much and it's hard to get through the door to put your name on the wait list (it's a big chalkboard on the wall that isn't really that obvious if you walk straight into the building) and there is no great place to wait. Three seats inside and standing room only on a small sidewalk outside. Your best bet is to put your name in line, walk down to Philz coffee and have a good drink then come back in time to get your seat. We went at noon on Sunday and had a 45 minute wait.

    This place is beautiful inside but tightly packed. Love the decor which features giant mirrors and feels like a cafe from Paris.

    We tried the beignets which were fine and our food was delicious. Lots of cheesy grits and gravy but the pork belly was pretty crunchy. Almost like burnt bacon. It tasted heavenly but I am not sure if that is how it should be cooked. Other than that, everything was very good.

    This wouldn't be my first choice for Cajun food but a great place for trying new and delicious food.

    Pros:
    Good service
    Great food
    Cool atmosphere

    Cons:
    Parking - metered on a busy street
    Very cramped table
    Long wait for a table on the weekend

    I thought Brenda's stood out from the moment I entered. You go from walking in the gritty Tenderloin to entering into a completely different environment. For those originally from the South, I hope it reminds you of home and you can gauge how great or not so great Brenda's truly is.

    Almost exactly 9 years since my last visit and what a difference. Looking back, I probably ordered the wrong things. None of what I had before was part of the house favorites.

    This time, I got all the right stuff:

    -Crawfish Beignets: If you're not into sweets, this is perfect. It's like an awesome version of a Hot Pocket. It's huge. It's full of cheese and crawfish. It comes out hot and gooey. It's dusted with a Cajun seasoning that's flavorful but not overpowering. In fact, I rubbed my beignet in all the seasoning that fell off onto my plate.

    -Hangtown Fry: It looks like a plain omelette when you get it but each bite of oyster makes it that much better. It's a big portion with a huge biscuit and a hefty bowl of buttery grits.

    -Shrimp and Grits: This is super flavorful and might induce heartburn for the weak, especially if you're having this early in the morning. At the very bottom of the large bowl are the grits. Next, you'll find a thick layer of melted cheddar. On top of that, you'll find the spicy tomato-bacon gravy. It was topped off with shrimp which was cooked tender and not over done at all. It's creamy, savory and heavy. I was only able to eat half so they packed the other half for me and it didn't look as much in the takeout container. So I think the bowl is slightly an illusion; looks bigger than it really is but the heaviness will fill you up quick.

    It has been quite a while but I don't remember the inside looking this hip and cool. The space has also expanded and I'm glad there was absolutely no wait at 10am on a Tuesday. I will definitely be taking any out-of-towners here in the future.

    11/10/2008Previous review

    3.5 Stars.

    Brenda's is such a cute little place for breakfast!  It's really small so I'm glad I went on a Monday morning when most people are at work.  At 10:45am, I got a seat for two right away.

    Beignets - This was my first time having these so I didn't know what to expect but they are much lighter than the American donut.  My bf originally had these at Cafe Du Monde in New Orleans and said they are more gooey there.  One order of the regular is $4 but there are 3 big pieces!  It looks like there is a lot of powdered sugar but it's necessary since without it, the beignets would be a bit bland.  They come out piping hot though... even steaming.  Next time I want to try the beignet flight: chocolate, granny smith apple, crawfish.

    Egg and Bacon Tartine ($9) - I got hash and this was my favorite item of the dish!  I was expecting shredded potatoes but these are actually seasoned potatoes.  Sad that they came out a little cold but even then, they were still flavorful.  If you're unfamiliar like I was, a "tartine" is an open-faced sandwich.  It was topped with bacon, then a THICK layer of scrambled egg, then a thin layer of gruyere, with the tomato-bacon relish on top of a French roll.  Without the relish, this sandwich would be nothing!!  Okay maybe not exactly but the relish is sweet and tastes like tomatoes but not tart like tomatoes.  I wanted more of it.  The eggs were a little too thick for my liking so I scraped it off.

    I had a bite of the bf's Andouille and Cheddar Omelette; the sausage was tasty and the cheese was gooey!  He got less hash than I did but his dish came with a biscuit!  The biscuits were also lukewarm when they came out (seeing a trend?) and on the flaky side.

    During my meal, I desperately needed to go to the bathroom but it didn't seem anywhere in sight.  The server told me I just have to go through the kitchen and it was slightly daunting.  The floor is very oily and I kept envisioning myself tripping over onto a hot stove.  Do not rule the possibility out because the stove was literally inches from me!  I ended up leaving my hat here so I came back a couple hours later to get it and found it on the floor by my table.  Thanks?  

    I want to come back for lunch.
